ual levels, anticipating later twentieth-century thinkers who fused the studies of mass communications and public opinion research. Terry N. Clark’s introduction, considered the premier guide to Tarde’s opus, accompanies this important work, reprinted here for the first time in forty years.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aSocial influence. 0aSociologyxHistoryy19th century. 0aSociologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aClark, Terry N.1 aClark, Terry N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Terry N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanowitz, Morris.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package Archive 1960-1989z978311066784440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226789798423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226789798.jpg  a978-3-11-066784-4  UChP eBook-Package Archive 1960-1989c1960d1989  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles